Issues.Body:
### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

service-worker

### Description

We are currently using a service worker in our Angular application to handle push notifications. We have noticed that the `handlePush` function of the service worker is parsing notifications in a non-standard way, which could lead to compatibility issues and maintain less maintainable code.

The current handlePush function has the following form:
```
async handlePush(data) {
    await this.broadcast({
        type: "PUSH",
        data
    });
    if (!data.notification || !data.notification.title) {
        return;
    }
    const desc = data.notification;
    let options = {};
    NOTIFICATION_OPTION_NAMES.filter((name) => desc.hasOwnProperty(name)).forEach((name) => options[name] = desc[name]);
    await this.scope.registration.showNotification(desc["title"], options);
}
```

This implementation uses a non-standard object structure for notifications and performs unnecessary checks.

### Proposed solution

We propose a more standardized way of handling push notifications in the `handlePush` function. Here is the proposed new implementation:
```
async handlePush(data) {
    await this.broadcast({
        type: "PUSH",
        data
    });
    if (!data || !data.title) {
        return;
    }
    const desc = data;
    let options = {};
    NOTIFICATION_OPTION_NAMES.filter((name) => desc.hasOwnProperty(name)).forEach((name) => options[name] = desc[name]);
    await this.scope.registration.showNotification(desc["title"], options);
}
```

### Alternatives considered

This new implementation eliminates the need to check for the existence of the "notification" key and simplifies the code.

Material Web's new CSS styles do not have a configuration to skip variable fallback values. We are including these to help the transition to the new styles. Previously this would also add additional declarative fallback styles on top of variable defaults, but is turned off by the new flag `emit-declaration-fallback`. This new configuration will be pushed out this week

Before:
```
.mdc-checkbox {
    padding: calc((var(--mdc-checkbox-state-layer-size) - 18px) / 2);
    margin: calc((var(--mdc-checkbox-state-layer-size) - var(--mdc-checkbox-state-layer-size)) / 2);
}
```

After:
```
.mdc-checkbox {
    padding: calc((var(--mdc-checkbox-state-layer-size, 40px) - 18px) / 2);
    margin: calc((var(--mdc-checkbox-state-layer-size, 40px) - var(--mdc-checkbox-state-layer-size, 40px)) / 2);
}
```
